WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.440
Hello. My name is Marvin Heemeyer.

00:00:05.280 --> 00:00:12.380
Today is, let's see here, April 13, 2004.

00:00:14.180 --> 00:00:18.400
I am making this tape. I thought I should make it a year ago.

00:00:19.200 --> 00:00:21.960
Made part of it. Didn't like it.

00:00:23.400 --> 00:00:27.500
Really didn't think it would make any difference if I didn't make it, but a good friend of mine said I should make it.

00:00:27.500 --> 00:00:31.260
And he said I should sit down in front of a videotape machine and do it.

00:00:31.500 --> 00:00:35.440
But you're just going to have to take my word that this is Marvin Heemeyer.

00:00:35.519 --> 00:00:38.200
Serial number 503-689-471.

00:00:39.560 --> 00:00:43.280
And I'm living in Grand Lake, Colorado.

00:00:45.040 --> 00:00:52.240
And this tape is about my life since I came up here to Grand Lake in 1991.

00:00:52.240 --> 00:00:57.240
I moved up here in the fall of 1991 to...

00:00:57.500 --> 00:00:59.140
kind of take a six-month vacation.

00:00:59.920 --> 00:01:06.940
Had a guy and his wife who were leasing my muffler shop in Boulder at 4790 Pearl Street.

00:01:07.500 --> 00:01:10.780
Guy's name was Doug Branstetter with his wife.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:13.000
I forget her name right now, but...

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:15.900
Anyway, they were just on a probationary period.

00:01:16.039 --> 00:01:20.840
This guy had serious alcohol and drug abuse problems in the past.

00:01:20.840 --> 00:01:24.880
Supposedly he was cleaned up. I didn't know if he was or not, but he kept pestering me for jobs.

00:01:25.080 --> 00:01:26.420
Finally, I said he could lease the place.

00:01:27.120 --> 00:01:27.440
Anyway...

00:01:27.500 --> 00:01:31.280
He ran it for four and a half years and everything went to hell.

00:01:31.380 --> 00:01:33.680
I guess he got a divorce and different things happened.

00:01:34.260 --> 00:01:35.240
I ended up getting it back.

00:01:36.620 --> 00:01:40.000
And then I let another guy come along.

00:01:40.520 --> 00:01:45.580
I was working down there, working up in Granby, actually, at the muffler shop I had in Granby.

00:01:46.060 --> 00:01:48.580
And in Boulder.

00:01:49.560 --> 00:01:52.260
Had two different people working for me.

00:01:52.580 --> 00:01:54.140
One in Boulder, her name was Christy.

00:01:54.240 --> 00:01:56.620
She was from someplace up in South Dakota.

00:01:57.500 --> 00:02:01.100
Great worker. Wonderful person. I really appreciated her.

00:02:01.680 --> 00:02:03.320
And then a little girl up here.

00:02:07.040 --> 00:02:07.480
Dawn...

00:02:07.480 --> 00:02:10.520
Gretchen Allison was her name.

00:02:11.360 --> 00:02:11.900
And anyway...

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:17.140
So I was running both businesses and this other guy came along named Doug Davis.

00:02:17.140 --> 00:02:19.640
He worked at Midas for about nine years as a manager.

00:02:20.320 --> 00:02:21.820
He wanted to be a working manager.

00:02:22.140 --> 00:02:23.500
So he took over the place.

00:02:23.700 --> 00:02:26.880
I gave him a little better deal than the other Doug Branstetter had.

00:02:27.500 --> 00:02:28.780
Because Doug seemed to...

00:02:28.780 --> 00:02:31.960
The first Doug seemed to have a lot of problems making his payments last year or so.

00:02:32.100 --> 00:02:33.640
But we have...

00:02:33.640 --> 00:02:36.080
I believe they were for one reason.

00:02:36.380 --> 00:02:38.100
And he would never admit it, though.

00:02:38.920 --> 00:02:41.460
That's the same way that this Doug Davis, he finally left.

00:02:41.860 --> 00:02:43.200
He left here about a month ago.

00:02:43.280 --> 00:02:44.200
I got the place back.

00:02:44.380 --> 00:02:45.600
The landlord evicted him.

00:02:45.680 --> 00:02:47.360
Old Harold Pelley down there evicted him.

00:02:49.320 --> 00:02:52.460
And anyway, I took it back.

00:02:52.460 --> 00:02:57.040
And hopefully I got it sold to a real nice guy and his wife.

00:02:57.500 --> 00:03:00.780
Jeff Sterling and his wife Jennifer.

00:03:01.240 --> 00:03:03.500
They should be taking over the first of...

00:03:07.260 --> 00:03:07.860
May.

00:03:08.100 --> 00:03:08.720
First of May.

00:03:09.580 --> 00:03:13.420
Anyway, so I've cashed out of it finally.

00:03:13.780 --> 00:03:14.700
And I'm done with it.

00:03:15.180 --> 00:03:16.480
And anyway...

00:03:16.480 --> 00:03:17.600
Anyway, I moved up here.

00:03:17.640 --> 00:03:18.520
That's my history in Boulder.

00:03:18.940 --> 00:03:20.000
This is my history up here.

00:03:20.220 --> 00:03:23.320
I came up here and after a few months of living here,

00:03:23.320 --> 00:03:26.580
I realized this guy down there in Boulder was doing better than I ever thought he would.

00:03:27.500 --> 00:03:29.600
So it was all based on...

00:03:29.600 --> 00:03:32.880
He kept it based on whether he performed or not.

00:03:32.960 --> 00:03:34.500
Of course, he was making all kinds of money.

00:03:34.680 --> 00:03:35.920
So I was happy.

00:03:35.980 --> 00:03:36.560
He was happy.

00:03:36.680 --> 00:03:38.600
And I realized he was going to keep it.

00:03:39.980 --> 00:03:41.140
So it came springtime.

00:03:41.280 --> 00:03:44.500
It's probably April, I'm thinking.

00:03:45.120 --> 00:03:49.200
I decided that I probably ought to buy some property up here to have something to do.

00:03:49.200 --> 00:03:56.620
So I looked at this three lots and the two little cabins that I'm living in here right now.

00:03:57.500 --> 00:04:00.400
And I had a beautiful view.

00:04:00.580 --> 00:04:02.060
And the price was really cheap.

00:04:02.120 --> 00:04:02.820
So I bought them.

00:04:04.160 --> 00:04:08.880
And I figured I'd spend the next year until this dud guy folded.

00:04:09.740 --> 00:04:11.440
Because I didn't know how long it would last.

00:04:11.620 --> 00:04:14.380
I figured I'd just fix this house up, these cabins up.

00:04:15.480 --> 00:04:17.160
Well, then a friend of mine from Boulder.

00:04:17.680 --> 00:04:18.420
A friend.

00:04:18.680 --> 00:04:20.200
He was a friend to a point.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:24.560
I guess you'd call him a friend.

00:04:24.560 --> 00:04:26.520
We did a lot of snowmobiling together.

00:04:26.680 --> 00:04:27.480
He met me.

00:04:27.580 --> 00:04:28.940
He threw the muffler shop down there.

00:04:29.040 --> 00:04:31.440
He had a DJ's auto care down there.

00:04:32.400 --> 00:04:33.900
Or Dr. John's auto care.

00:04:34.600 --> 00:04:37.360
And I did a lot of exhaust work for him.

00:04:37.380 --> 00:04:38.240
And he was a snowmobiler.

00:04:38.560 --> 00:04:39.960
So we started snowmobiling together.

00:04:40.380 --> 00:04:43.160
Without a doubt, I knew he had some problems with dope.

00:04:43.380 --> 00:04:46.060
As far as marijuana and drugs were concerned.

00:04:46.120 --> 00:04:47.220
I just didn't know how bad it was.

00:04:47.440 --> 00:04:50.040
You've got to just kind of ignore that stuff in today's day and age.

00:04:50.500 --> 00:04:52.500
You go out there and you find somebody who's a good rider.

00:04:52.620 --> 00:04:53.480
You ride with them.

00:04:53.480 --> 00:04:54.720
We had a lot of fun together.

00:04:55.380 --> 00:04:56.480
Anyway, he...

00:04:57.480 --> 00:05:01.980
He called me and said he was looking for a place up here to start a garage.

00:05:03.580 --> 00:05:07.820
And he already owned a cabin up here up there on Coff County Road 4.

00:05:08.940 --> 00:05:12.580
And I said I'd take a look.

00:05:12.580 --> 00:05:13.580
See if I could find anything.

00:05:15.420 --> 00:05:16.340
So I started looking.

00:05:16.520 --> 00:05:22.100
And there was a guy named Pepper had a little garage down there south of Grand Lake.

00:05:24.380 --> 00:05:27.040
Just north of the Ski-Doo dealership that had a bay door on it.

00:05:27.240 --> 00:05:27.440
And...

00:05:27.440 --> 00:05:28.900
He didn't want anything big.

00:05:29.020 --> 00:05:32.040
So I told him about that.

00:05:32.120 --> 00:05:34.760
And then I happened to cross a piece of property down there in Granby.

00:05:35.740 --> 00:05:37.420
It was an old concrete plant.

00:05:37.420 --> 00:05:38.980
And the guy had gone bankrupt.

00:05:39.660 --> 00:05:41.960
And had an auction.

00:05:42.340 --> 00:05:44.440
And gotten rid of all the stuff he had.

00:05:44.460 --> 00:05:45.960
And left a bunch of junk there.

00:05:46.880 --> 00:05:47.860
It's my understanding.

00:05:49.420 --> 00:05:53.120
But it had a 3,000 square foot building with three bay doors.

00:05:53.380 --> 00:05:54.900
That were huge.

00:05:55.020 --> 00:05:56.340
It was a great building.

00:05:56.440 --> 00:05:57.420
It wasn't the best location.

00:05:57.440 --> 00:05:58.900
But it was a good building.

00:05:59.340 --> 00:06:00.560
And it had two acres of ground.

00:06:01.700 --> 00:06:03.160
And I talked to him about it.

00:06:03.180 --> 00:06:04.040
And he said that would be great.

00:06:04.100 --> 00:06:05.540
I think he even came up and looked at it.

00:06:05.540 --> 00:06:06.240
I can't remember.

00:06:06.360 --> 00:06:08.420
But anyway, he said that he was interested.

00:06:08.560 --> 00:06:11.220
So we talked to a realtor named Jeff Crane.

00:06:11.300 --> 00:06:12.540
Or I talked to him, I should say.

00:06:13.520 --> 00:06:16.900
And this was about a month before they were going to have this FDIC auction.

00:06:18.740 --> 00:06:22.360
So Jeff says that he'd sell me the property.

00:06:23.680 --> 00:06:25.860
We could write up a contract on it if I wanted it.

00:06:25.860 --> 00:06:27.360
But he figured it was worth about...

00:06:27.440 --> 00:06:31.080
$110,000 or so or more.

00:06:31.280 --> 00:06:32.480
And I kind of laughed.

00:06:32.600 --> 00:06:34.520
And I said, you know, there's no way it's worth that.

00:06:34.640 --> 00:06:40.280
I mean, the property up here was just so depressed in 1991 and 92.

00:06:40.580 --> 00:06:41.620
It was terrible.

00:06:42.280 --> 00:06:45.500
And I didn't foresee any kind of future up here.

00:06:45.640 --> 00:06:47.720
I mean, I hadn't ever lived in the mountains before.

00:06:48.240 --> 00:06:52.460
It just didn't seem like a good thing to be buying at that kind of a price.

00:06:52.460 --> 00:06:55.860
So I told him, I said, I'd wait until the FDIC had their auction.

00:06:56.940 --> 00:06:57.300
And...

00:06:57.300 --> 00:06:59.320
I and John talked it over.

00:06:59.400 --> 00:07:03.260
And we agreed that, you know, I'd pay $66,000 for it.

00:07:03.620 --> 00:07:04.400
At the max.

00:07:04.480 --> 00:07:06.300
And if it went higher than that, we wouldn't buy it.

00:07:06.320 --> 00:07:06.820
He didn't want it.

00:07:08.420 --> 00:07:08.740
So...

00:07:08.740 --> 00:07:13.020
The time came and then he paid me a certain amount.

00:07:13.500 --> 00:07:19.420
I can't remember if he was going to pay me more than $66,000 for buying it for him.

00:07:19.440 --> 00:07:21.280
Or if I was just going to finance it to him.

00:07:21.520 --> 00:07:23.820
I know I was going to finance it to him.

00:07:24.140 --> 00:07:26.440
But I don't know if it was $66,000.

00:07:26.580 --> 00:07:27.140
Or if there was...

00:07:27.140 --> 00:07:27.560
It was going to be more.

00:07:27.620 --> 00:07:28.919
Anyway, it doesn't make any difference.

00:07:31.360 --> 00:07:33.620
Come time for the auction, I...

00:07:33.620 --> 00:07:40.180
Jeff Crane was down there with four older guys who were looking to invest some money in some FDIC properties.

00:07:40.380 --> 00:07:43.099
And I think there was about 160 properties for sale that day.

00:07:44.780 --> 00:07:45.260
And...

00:07:45.260 --> 00:07:48.280
Anyway, this one finally came up for bid.

00:07:49.620 --> 00:07:50.140
And...

00:07:50.140 --> 00:07:50.719
They...

00:07:50.719 --> 00:07:54.979
Well, actually, first they told me that there was a EPA audit against the place.

00:07:55.099 --> 00:07:55.840
Which was a...

00:07:55.840 --> 00:07:56.979
They were recommending a

00:07:57.140 --> 00:07:58.039
$26,000 cleanup.

00:07:58.260 --> 00:08:01.360
They had all these surveys done by Chen Northern.

00:08:01.960 --> 00:08:03.000
Was the...

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:07.200
Was the company contracted to look at it.

00:08:07.280 --> 00:08:09.900
But anyway, come to find out later.

00:08:10.039 --> 00:08:14.479
Later on that FDIC had done a lot of the cleanup that they had recommended.

00:08:14.820 --> 00:08:15.640
And I don't know.

00:08:15.680 --> 00:08:17.300
For some reason, I didn't realize that.

00:08:17.440 --> 00:08:20.340
So, I told John about it.

00:08:20.620 --> 00:08:22.140
Or it came up for sale.

00:08:22.140 --> 00:08:23.719
It came up on the block.

00:08:24.419 --> 00:08:27.099
And they had a bid for $35,000.

00:08:27.140 --> 00:08:28.900
From some guy up in front.

00:08:30.080 --> 00:08:32.699
And so, we were going to pay $66,000.

00:08:32.799 --> 00:08:33.919
I started waving at them.

00:08:33.960 --> 00:08:34.679
They couldn't see me.

00:08:35.340 --> 00:08:36.640
So, finally, they caught my bid.

00:08:36.740 --> 00:08:38.400
So, I got a bid for $40,000.

00:08:39.059 --> 00:08:40.960
This other guy, I couldn't believe it.

00:08:41.240 --> 00:08:42.600
I didn't know who he was.

00:08:42.679 --> 00:08:43.780
He jumped up on his chair.

00:08:43.919 --> 00:08:45.120
That's how I knew where he was.

00:08:45.580 --> 00:08:46.380
And I was looking back.

00:08:46.420 --> 00:08:47.980
And, of course, he bid $45,000.

00:08:48.699 --> 00:08:50.380
And, of course, I bid $50,000.

00:08:51.240 --> 00:08:52.780
And I was waiting for him to bid.

00:08:52.819 --> 00:08:53.380
And he wouldn't bid.

00:08:54.900 --> 00:08:58.000
And so, I got the property for $50,000.

00:09:00.360 --> 00:09:04.580
And this guy, come to find out, his name was Cody Docheff.

00:09:04.620 --> 00:09:06.819
He came back there and introduced himself to me.

00:09:06.960 --> 00:09:11.160
About the rudest, most arrogant person.

00:09:12.180 --> 00:09:14.880
I mean, this guy is just a fucking asshole.

00:09:15.560 --> 00:09:18.319
Come back and just introduced himself, kind of,

00:09:18.560 --> 00:09:22.360
by just giving me a tongue lashing for about 10 minutes

00:09:22.360 --> 00:09:24.260
about, you know, who I thought I was

00:09:24.260 --> 00:09:25.800
and what I was going to do with the property.

00:09:25.800 --> 00:09:27.080
And I explained to him I was buying.

00:09:27.080 --> 00:09:27.120
And he said, well, I'm going to buy a property.

00:09:27.120 --> 00:09:32.460
And I said, well, I'll tell you, I'll sell you the property.

00:09:32.640 --> 00:09:34.620
I said, we were going to pay $66,000.

00:09:35.700 --> 00:09:39.360
And, you know, I told him I was selling it to John Kleiner,

00:09:39.500 --> 00:09:41.140
who was going to start an automotive store there.

00:09:41.380 --> 00:09:43.460
And he didn't want to have anything to do with it.

00:09:43.500 --> 00:09:44.120
He said, bullshit.

00:09:44.400 --> 00:09:46.960
He said, I only got, Gus Harris was his buddy there,

00:09:47.040 --> 00:09:48.120
sitting beside him, I guess.

00:09:48.560 --> 00:09:51.680
And Gus was sponsoring the whole financing on this thing.

00:09:51.800 --> 00:09:54.680
And Gus wasn't going to pay more than $50,000 for it.

00:09:54.900 --> 00:09:56.620
And I said, well, I'm sorry.

00:09:56.620 --> 00:09:59.620
But I says, you know, I can't just not come down here

00:09:59.620 --> 00:10:01.540
and spend my money and waste my time

00:10:01.540 --> 00:10:04.360
and not, you know, make some money on it.

00:10:04.380 --> 00:10:05.780
So I offered it to him that day

00:10:05.780 --> 00:10:07.640
for what I was going to sell it to John for.

00:10:07.880 --> 00:10:09.740
Because I could tell the guy was pissed off.

00:10:09.780 --> 00:10:12.140
And I wasn't there to piss off any people.

00:10:12.300 --> 00:10:13.820
I mean, this is the only guy

00:10:13.820 --> 00:10:16.200
of all the properties that sold before his

00:10:16.200 --> 00:10:19.020
that was doing any screaming at anybody during the auction.

00:10:19.740 --> 00:10:23.420
I mean, 160 people, or 160 properties were sold that day.

00:10:23.460 --> 00:10:25.600
And this is the only fool that didn't come down there

00:10:25.600 --> 00:10:26.560
with enough

00:10:26.560 --> 00:10:26.920
money

00:10:26.920 --> 00:10:28.060
to buy his property.

00:10:28.219 --> 00:10:30.160
I mean, this shows you how day late

00:10:30.160 --> 00:10:31.640
and a dollar short this fool is.

00:10:32.060 --> 00:10:33.400
You know, he thinks he's going to go down there.

00:10:33.459 --> 00:10:34.959
I mean, he screwed the whole town of Granby

00:10:34.959 --> 00:10:37.599
over the years by going bankrupt.

00:10:38.459 --> 00:10:41.300
And, you know, I guess this guy's pretty dramatic.

00:10:41.500 --> 00:10:44.140
He tried to, he faked a suicide

00:10:44.140 --> 00:10:46.780
jumping off a windmill or some hot, tall building

00:10:46.780 --> 00:10:49.319
out there by his place, by Hot Sulphur Springs.

00:10:49.420 --> 00:10:52.719
Anyway, you know, he's just, he's going off on me

00:10:52.719 --> 00:10:55.119
and wasn't going to pay any more money.

00:10:55.119 --> 00:10:56.119
And I says, well, I'm sorry.

00:10:56.239 --> 00:10:56.540
I gotta

00:10:56.560 --> 00:10:57.660
have $66,000.

00:10:57.959 --> 00:11:00.260
I'll let John go find something else.

00:11:00.439 --> 00:11:02.400
You know, I'm just trying to be a peacemaker here.

00:11:02.959 --> 00:11:04.219
But I got to make some money.

00:11:04.359 --> 00:11:05.500
He wouldn't have anything to do with it.

00:11:06.219 --> 00:11:08.119
So, you know, I calmed him down.

00:11:08.239 --> 00:11:10.400
I mean, I talked to this guy forever, it seemed like.

00:11:10.780 --> 00:11:13.680
Everybody around me, they couldn't believe this asshole.

00:11:14.500 --> 00:11:16.699
And anyway, so we closed the deal.

00:11:16.739 --> 00:11:17.160
He left.

00:11:17.239 --> 00:11:17.780
He went away.

00:11:18.680 --> 00:11:25.359
And I went and had Jeff Crane sign the broker's statement

00:11:25.359 --> 00:11:27.540
that I was purchasing this property and

00:11:27.540 --> 00:11:29.520
And as a matter of fact,

00:11:29.599 --> 00:11:31.239
going back here a little bit,

00:11:31.520 --> 00:11:33.000
when I had first looked at the property

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:36.760
and Jeff had tried to sell it to me,

00:11:36.979 --> 00:11:39.520
I had asked him if the former owner

00:11:39.520 --> 00:11:41.739
was interested in purchasing the property

00:11:41.739 --> 00:11:43.380
at this FDIC auction.

00:11:43.560 --> 00:11:44.760
He said he didn't know.

00:11:45.420 --> 00:11:47.699
Well, then I called the FDIC to look at it

00:11:47.699 --> 00:11:49.020
because there was a number to call.

00:11:49.800 --> 00:11:52.219
And they called an agent there in Granby,

00:11:52.260 --> 00:11:54.619
a real estate agent named Peter Colley.

00:11:55.319 --> 00:11:56.439
So Peter went

00:11:56.440 --> 00:11:59.960
out and bought a padlock and I went down there with a cutting torch and we cut the lock that

00:11:59.960 --> 00:12:04.600
was on the building off so I could look at it and then of course he put his new padlock on

00:12:05.160 --> 00:12:09.800
and uh he showed me the building and it looked like it'd be a good building so anyway I asked

00:12:09.800 --> 00:12:15.400
this Peter Colley also if the former owner had any if he knew if the homeowner had any interest

00:12:15.400 --> 00:12:22.280
in buying the building and of course he told me he didn't know so okay well I feel that my job is

00:12:22.280 --> 00:12:26.600
done you know I I'm gonna go to the auction so we did and I ended up buying it we closed on the deal

00:12:27.160 --> 00:12:33.160
and uh you know I came back up to Grand Lake and I got a hold of John Kleiner and told him

00:12:33.160 --> 00:12:40.360
that what had happened and this is like I said it was about April of 1992. and uh told him explained

00:12:40.360 --> 00:12:44.199
to him that there was an EPA audit against the property because there were some oil stains on

00:12:44.199 --> 00:12:48.760
the property there had been an oil fill barrel and you know I don't know if it was that day or a

00:12:48.760 --> 00:12:51.959
couple weeks later whenever he you know he just didn't want anything to do with the property all

00:12:51.959 --> 00:12:52.199
of a

00:12:52.200 --> 00:12:57.020
sudden. And of course, I hadn't taken any deposit from him, so I was stuck with

00:12:57.020 --> 00:13:01.520
the property. But he didn't want anything to do with it because of the audit. And of

00:13:01.520 --> 00:13:08.980
course, he was from Boulder, and Boulder is pretty, what do you want to call it, eco-Nazi

00:13:08.980 --> 00:13:18.400
type. They think they're going to save the world. And that was his fear. I mean, there

00:13:18.400 --> 00:13:22.180
were a lot of regulations about dumping oil and all that stuff. So, he didn't want anything

00:13:22.180 --> 00:13:25.380
to do with it all of a sudden. Well, I don't know if he didn't have the money or just got

00:13:25.380 --> 00:13:29.439
cold feet or what, but I'm stuck with this property, so heck, I don't know what to do

00:13:29.439 --> 00:13:39.199
with it. So, that summer, I'm pretty sure it was that summer, I tried cleaning the property

00:13:39.199 --> 00:13:47.560
up. It might have been even 92. I may have just let it sit there. I know I let it sit

00:13:47.560 --> 00:13:47.780
there.

00:13:48.400 --> 00:13:55.420
I didn't have any equipment. I didn't clean it up. But anyway, eventually, I did buy a

00:13:55.420 --> 00:14:05.740
backhoe, and I bought a dump truck from my dad, a beat truck. And, you know, I started

00:14:05.740 --> 00:14:12.360
cleaning the property up and hauling the steel away. Hauled it over to Geisendorfer's property.

00:14:12.520 --> 00:14:17.040
He had a guy that was cutting up steel over there and selling steel, and this kid wanted

00:14:17.040 --> 00:14:18.380
it. So, we just high-hauled

00:14:18.380 --> 00:14:25.200
everything over there. And, basically, got the place cleaned up pretty nice. Rented a bulldozer, a little D3

00:14:25.200 --> 00:14:33.200
from Linky. What's his name? Dick Linky, Southwood Granby there. Pretty good, real good guy.

00:14:33.200 --> 00:14:39.060
And he delivered it over there, and I leveled out the ground and the stuff, you know, tried

00:14:39.060 --> 00:14:44.680
to make it look pretty presentable, you know. And I didn't know what to do with it. The

00:14:44.680 --> 00:14:47.380
guy in Boulder was doing great. So, finally, I decided

00:14:47.380 --> 00:14:48.380
that I'd start a muffler

00:14:48.380 --> 00:14:56.760
shop and I think I started that either late 92 or late 93. I don't remember anymore. But, you

00:14:56.760 --> 00:15:00.740
know, I just started putting on mufflers. I went down in Denver and found a used bender

00:15:00.740 --> 00:15:06.300
and brought a used toy stuff that I had down there in Boulder and set it up and started

00:15:06.300 --> 00:15:12.040
putting on mufflers and advertising and everything. And, you know, figured I was going to do a

00:15:12.040 --> 00:15:17.040
good - good thing. You know, this was maybe an opportunity for me.

00:15:18.040 --> 00:15:25.420
Anyway, I'm getting ahead of myself. In 92, I was cleaning the property

00:15:25.420 --> 00:15:38.760
up. Yeah, that's the way I went. Because in the summer of 92, after I bought it, a guy

00:15:38.760 --> 00:15:46.079
named Bud Wilson, who is the superintendent of the water and sanitation district down

00:15:46.079 --> 00:15:47.040
there in Granby,

00:15:47.040 --> 00:15:48.040
came to

00:15:48.040 --> 00:15:49.260
me and said that

00:15:49.260 --> 00:15:49.360
[Dead air]

00:15:49.360 --> 00:15:55.099
they wanted me to hook on to the - the annexed end of the water and sanitation districts.

00:15:55.099 --> 00:15:58.900
So, I said great. I says what - what do I have to do?

00:15:58.900 --> 00:16:05.760
I says do I - is there - do I have to get an attourney invovled or what? He said naw he said he'd do all the paperwork and

00:16:05.760 --> 00:16:12.839
there was some kind of fee I think that I had to pay but I don't remember anymore but anyway I was supposed to go to a meeting in

00:16:12.839 --> 00:16:13.920
September, I

00:16:13.920 --> 00:16:15.939
believe it was and get annexed

00:16:15.939 --> 00:16:16.079
in

00:16:16.079 --> 00:16:16.339
to the

00:16:16.339 --> 00:16:16.640
water

00:16:16.640 --> 00:16:17.120
and san.

00:16:17.120 --> 00:16:17.240
[Dead air]

00:16:17.240 --> 00:16:17.900
[Dead air]

00:16:17.900 --> 00:16:18.040
And

00:16:18.040 --> 00:16:19.620
so we did.

00:16:19.760 --> 00:16:20.500
I went to the meeting,

00:16:22.099 --> 00:16:29.660
and I just expected it to go through.

00:16:29.660 --> 00:16:33.099
It was unbelievable what happened at that meeting.

00:16:34.040 --> 00:16:41.060
The main topic of concern that they had with me being annexed into the district

00:16:41.060 --> 00:16:46.420
was that they didn't have a maintenance easement across the property

00:16:46.420 --> 00:16:48.099
that was just south of me.

00:16:48.760 --> 00:16:50.699
It was owned by Gus Harris.

00:16:51.680 --> 00:16:55.579
And they had put in a watered sewer line years before,

00:16:55.579 --> 00:16:58.680
but it supposedly hadn't gotten this maintenance easement.

00:16:59.599 --> 00:17:03.699
And Gus Harris wasn't going to give it to them or something.

00:17:04.319 --> 00:17:06.040
You know, I'm not really sure how that all worked,

00:17:06.119 --> 00:17:08.679
but this maintenance easement was a pretty big obstacle.

00:17:09.260 --> 00:17:10.720
And they basically told me,

00:17:10.760 --> 00:17:11.040
the board,

00:17:11.060 --> 00:17:12.839
in the fall of 92,

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:16.179
that I would never have water and sewer there

00:17:16.179 --> 00:17:19.740
until I got this maintenance easement from this Gus Harris guy.

00:17:21.159 --> 00:17:23.020
Well, I was a little upset because, you know,

00:17:23.119 --> 00:17:24.819
he was a super, Bud was a superintendent,

00:17:25.020 --> 00:17:27.020
and this was supposed to, I thought this was a done deal.

00:17:27.679 --> 00:17:29.300
So, you know, I left the meeting,

00:17:29.440 --> 00:17:31.480
and I didn't need to listen anymore.

00:17:31.580 --> 00:17:32.020
They're crap.

00:17:32.080 --> 00:17:33.419
They wasted a lot of my time.

00:17:34.060 --> 00:17:39.060
And, you know, I knew that there was some animosity in the community.

00:17:41.060 --> 00:17:46.000
I had been getting my hair cut down at this place called Lana's,

00:17:46.500 --> 00:17:50.360
and she had told me about how this Cody Docheff guy had tried to kill himself

00:17:50.360 --> 00:17:53.000
and had screwed a lot of people in the community

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:56.740
and, you know, had gone bankrupt.

00:17:57.460 --> 00:18:02.399
And he was kind of, they were kind of glad that he wasn't there anymore,

00:18:02.560 --> 00:18:04.139
that he was outside of town.

00:18:04.139 --> 00:18:10.300
He had moved up into Dick Thompson's gravel pit,

00:18:10.419 --> 00:18:11.040
north of,

00:18:11.060 --> 00:18:12.960
where that location was about a mile,

00:18:13.700 --> 00:18:16.320
and was doing concrete, making concrete out of there again.

00:18:17.139 --> 00:18:17.740
But anyway,

00:18:18.740 --> 00:18:22.540
what the heck was my point?

00:18:23.399 --> 00:18:30.240
This Lana had, oh, she told me how upset everybody in the community was

00:18:30.240 --> 00:18:32.520
that, at the FDIC,

00:18:33.440 --> 00:18:40.760
because what had happened was they had that big savings and loan failure scandal,

00:18:41.060 --> 00:18:42.600
back in the

00:18:42.600 --> 00:18:43.679
late 70s early

00:18:43.679 --> 00:18:43.740
80s

00:18:43.740 --> 00:18:49.159
and everybody blamed the FDIC for this plant's failure

00:18:49.159 --> 00:18:52.540
and other people's problems that they'd had up there

00:18:52.540 --> 00:18:58.580
because what had happened is these people with the savings and loans failed,

00:18:58.780 --> 00:19:01.060
these people that owned property and stuff up there

00:19:01.060 --> 00:19:03.240
didn't have any place to make payments.

00:19:04.300 --> 00:19:07.320
So what they did, they didn't know what to do,

00:19:07.320 --> 00:19:10.179
so instead of, you know, putting the money aside every month,

00:19:11.060 --> 00:19:14.800
supposedly, they went out and spent the money.

00:19:15.399 --> 00:19:17.679
Well, then after a couple of years or whatever,

00:19:17.740 --> 00:19:19.139
whatever it took to straighten those deals,

00:19:19.320 --> 00:19:20.740
that savings and loan thing out,

00:19:21.240 --> 00:19:23.220
FDIC wanted their money all at once

00:19:23.220 --> 00:19:25.100
from these people that hadn't made these payments

00:19:25.100 --> 00:19:28.320
to these collapsed savings and loans places.

00:19:29.080 --> 00:19:30.879
And these people hadn't, didn't have the money.

00:19:32.060 --> 00:19:36.560
And so the FDIC, of course, was foreclosing on these properties.

00:19:36.560 --> 00:19:38.320
So everybody up there hated the FDIC.

00:19:38.980 --> 00:19:40.639
You know, didn't like their practices.

00:19:40.899 --> 00:19:41.040
And, of course,

00:19:41.060 --> 00:19:46.040
here I am, I'm a beneficiary of the FDIC's actions,

00:19:46.379 --> 00:19:49.220
and so I found this out later.

00:19:49.399 --> 00:19:51.300
You know, people are pretty angry with me.

00:19:51.659 --> 00:19:54.200
You know, they didn't know how to play by the rules.

00:19:54.320 --> 00:19:57.200
I played within the parameters of what was supposed to be done.

00:19:57.300 --> 00:19:59.379
There were 160 properties sold that day,

00:19:59.700 --> 00:20:02.720
and I bought it just like everybody else bought their property.

00:20:03.280 --> 00:20:06.460
And, you know, there's no reason why,

00:20:06.540 --> 00:20:07.860
why didn't this guy have,

00:20:07.860 --> 00:20:10.020
why didn't this guy have enough money

00:20:10.020 --> 00:20:10.899
to buy this property?

00:20:10.900 --> 00:20:12.660
I mean, it was an auction.

00:20:12.660 --> 00:20:16.140
He should have known that there was going to be people bidding against him.

00:20:16.140 --> 00:20:20.900
But I honestly believe he thought he was going to get it for next to nothing.

00:20:20.900 --> 00:20:27.140
And I believe that because I think the word was out in the community that he wanted it.

00:20:27.140 --> 00:20:32.260
And personally, I think the two realtors that showed it to me knew this.

00:20:32.260 --> 00:20:36.660
And they just didn't want the guy in the community.

00:20:36.660 --> 00:20:39.420
So they told me that they didn't know that he was bidding on it,

00:20:39.420 --> 00:20:40.740
or that he wanted it.

00:20:40.740 --> 00:20:42.740
But I knew that I would have talked to him.

00:20:42.740 --> 00:20:46.260
I would have called him and found out what the deal was.

00:20:46.260 --> 00:20:48.260
But anyway,

00:20:50.500 --> 00:20:52.500
we, I'm a little disappointed.

00:20:53.380 --> 00:20:58.100
And one thing they told me was to stay in touch with the superintendent

00:20:58.100 --> 00:20:59.300
in case anything changed.

00:20:59.300 --> 00:21:01.460
Well, of course I'll do that.

00:21:01.460 --> 00:21:03.140
You know, but that was kind of,

00:21:03.780 --> 00:21:08.420
kind of a mistake on my part because it shouldn't have been my responsibility

00:21:08.420 --> 00:21:10.580
to keep track of the superintendent.

00:21:10.580 --> 00:21:11.379
Which I did.

00:21:11.379 --> 00:21:15.699
Because I mean, I took this Bud Wilson out for breakfast on more than one occasion.

00:21:15.699 --> 00:21:18.260
He spent a lot of time out there at my shop.

00:21:18.260 --> 00:21:26.899
I sold him a Woos, W-U- apostrophe-S, small wheel drive, little dump, garden tractor.

00:21:26.899 --> 00:21:29.780
And I mean, I got along and this guy was a pretty good guy.

00:21:29.780 --> 00:21:31.540
At least that's the way he came across to me.

00:21:31.540 --> 00:21:34.260
So we had a pretty good relationship.

00:21:34.260 --> 00:21:37.699
And he never ever mentioned anything to me that anything was changing.

00:21:37.699 --> 00:21:38.820
He says it would, you know.

00:21:38.820 --> 00:21:40.340
But, you know, I don't know.

00:21:40.580 --> 00:21:42.179
It never did.

00:21:42.179 --> 00:21:43.060
Well, anyway.

00:21:44.659 --> 00:21:47.139
So I just go on about my business.

00:21:47.139 --> 00:21:53.460
And finally, I think it was in 94, nothing was happening.

00:21:53.460 --> 00:21:57.620
I mean, Bud wasn't telling me anything was changing or anything.

00:21:57.620 --> 00:22:05.540
So I went ahead and I said, well, I'm going to build me a boat storage building.

00:22:06.340 --> 00:22:10.500
And I'll design it so that I've got three 2,000 square foot

00:22:10.500 --> 00:22:10.900
units.

00:22:10.900 --> 00:22:14.420
And it was 50 feet wide by 120 feet long.

00:22:14.420 --> 00:22:17.380
And that we had three bay doors.

00:22:17.380 --> 00:22:20.500
And I was to put in three personnel doors.

00:22:20.500 --> 00:22:26.100
And I set the foundation up to have these three bay doors, three personnel doors, so

00:22:26.100 --> 00:22:32.340
that I could put inner walls in or divider walls in later on when I finally got on the

00:22:32.340 --> 00:22:32.980
water and sewer.

00:22:32.980 --> 00:22:37.060
So I could have it for rental.

00:22:37.060 --> 00:22:39.860
And this would become my, you know, a good retirement income.

00:22:39.860 --> 00:22:40.340
I could rent.

00:22:40.340 --> 00:22:43.939
The muffler shop building or sell the muffler shop business.

00:22:43.939 --> 00:22:48.179
I could subdivide the property because it was in the city already and fell under their

00:22:48.899 --> 00:22:49.780
subdivision rules.

00:22:49.780 --> 00:22:52.340
I mean, it was pretty much just a pre-approved thing.

00:22:52.340 --> 00:22:57.620
He just had to apply to the town, pay him the fees and, you know, follow the rules for

00:22:57.620 --> 00:22:59.139
what was HGB zoning.

00:22:59.939 --> 00:23:04.020
And HGB zoning, of course, was the best zoning you could possibly get.

00:23:04.020 --> 00:23:09.699
It included everything that was in commercial plus other things that wasn't.

00:23:09.700 --> 00:23:13.620
And there was no other zoning that would include more businesses than HGB.

00:23:15.300 --> 00:23:24.180
So anyway, I thought this was a good plan and I had this building built and in the fall

00:23:24.180 --> 00:23:27.860
of 94 just started advertising for boat storage.

00:23:27.860 --> 00:23:32.660
And of course, filled it up the very first year and I was pretty happy with that.

00:23:32.660 --> 00:23:34.980
So basically, it was paying the cost of the building.

00:23:36.820 --> 00:23:38.340
Well, you know, we just go along.

00:23:38.340 --> 00:23:38.820
I'm making

00:23:38.820 --> 00:23:39.380
lemons

00:23:39.380 --> 00:23:39.620
out

00:23:39.620 --> 00:23:39.700
of

00:23:39.700 --> 00:23:44.580
lemonade or lemonade out of lemons you know i can't get this darn water sewer going you know

00:23:45.140 --> 00:23:54.900
so uh i had the i had a well and a septic system uh which was doing its job and uh i figured that

00:23:54.900 --> 00:24:03.220
you know we'll just that'll work you know well of course and knowing that i couldn't uh get on uh

00:24:03.220 --> 00:24:11.460
put the other building on a well and sewer because i was in town uh i are well and septic because i

00:24:11.460 --> 00:24:15.860
was in town i was going to have to hook onto the water and sewer but not being able to do that

00:24:15.860 --> 00:24:19.700
because i didn't have this maintenance even easement and bud never told the thing to me

00:24:19.700 --> 00:24:24.500
yet i mean i'm building this building telling him what i'm going to do he knew what was going on but

00:24:24.500 --> 00:24:31.220
he never told me that anything had ever changed so i uh continue and do the do the boat storage

00:24:31.220 --> 00:24:32.900
and i'm doing muffler works and

00:24:33.220 --> 00:24:38.820
so forth by 98 i was doing i don't know i was making a real good income out of there along with

00:24:38.820 --> 00:24:46.020
what was coming out of boulder um well actually i got it back in 97 of course as i said and and then

00:24:46.020 --> 00:24:51.860
i gave it to this other doug davis guy but i was you know i get income out of boulder and income

00:24:51.860 --> 00:24:57.060
out of granby here and life was pretty good and you know i was taking a lot of time off because

00:24:57.060 --> 00:25:01.540
you know you don't have to maintain rentals with boat storage you know there wasn't that much

00:25:01.540 --> 00:25:03.200
muffler business up here i mean i

00:25:03.200 --> 00:25:07.600
only working three days a week in the wintertime there five days a week in the summer which was

00:25:07.600 --> 00:25:14.240
typical of any store i ever worked in as far as summer is concerned i never had any store ever

00:25:14.240 --> 00:25:18.800
open more than five days a week unless i'd open just open one up that i might work a saturday to

00:25:18.800 --> 00:25:26.480
you know make sure all the revenue was coming in anyway i uh i just was going along happy and in

00:25:26.480 --> 00:25:33.040
98 i believe it was in the fall this dochef guy oh

00:25:33.200 --> 00:25:41.200
or going way back to 92 you know without a doubt i made a mistake oh uh gus harris a couple of months

00:25:41.200 --> 00:25:46.160
after i bought this property this guy named gus harris who owned the property south of me

00:25:46.800 --> 00:25:53.600
uh was over over there doing some cutting on some steel and i went over to you know medium and see

00:25:53.600 --> 00:25:58.480
once if he was cooled down you know because i know that he was upset uh that he they didn't

00:25:58.480 --> 00:26:03.120
get this property and here he was i mean actually i'd had a couple of conversations before that time

00:26:03.200 --> 00:26:10.080
and he wanted he was willing to sell me the property then for uh seventeen thousand five

00:26:10.080 --> 00:26:15.440
hundred dollars and i basically told him this was two months after i bought it that i you know i

00:26:15.440 --> 00:26:21.440
didn't buy that property for myself that was there i bought it for somebody else he he was not wanting

00:26:21.440 --> 00:26:28.480
to uh uh buy it though oh john did want to buy it so i didn't want to spread myself too thin because

00:26:28.480 --> 00:26:33.040
the economy was so bad up here i told him i said i'll think about it and i'd get back to him

00:26:33.200 --> 00:26:39.440
well the truth of the matter is about a year later i i less than a year later i i went to him

00:26:39.440 --> 00:26:44.400
and i said yeah i said i'd like to buy that property and uh i said is that seventeen thousand

00:26:44.400 --> 00:26:49.120
dollar offer still good he says no he says i'd have to have twenty thousand dollars for it and

00:26:49.120 --> 00:26:53.760
i talked to his wife about this too about getting these contracts signed so i could buy it and he

00:26:53.760 --> 00:26:59.040
never would get back to me as far as getting this deal done so you know i'm still not wanting to

00:26:59.040 --> 00:27:03.120
push this deal because this is a small community and you know i need to get back to him and i'm not

00:27:03.200 --> 00:27:09.600
to fit in and uh i'm not you know pressured this is not one of those things i felt that you needed

00:27:09.600 --> 00:27:19.760
to do in a community where i'm new in anyway uh getting back to 98 now that earlier in 96 or 97

00:27:20.320 --> 00:27:24.640
gus harris had sold this two acres to this guy cody docheff

00:27:27.120 --> 00:27:33.120
and of course cody had made a comment that you know he wanted my property

00:27:33.200 --> 00:27:41.440
back in 97 it was and i had gone out and had a guy make an appraisal wilson was his name

00:27:42.800 --> 00:27:48.880
it was Dowdna who was the local appraiser here at Grand Lake still and it was Dowdna and Wilson

00:27:48.880 --> 00:27:53.920
and Wilson and Dowdna commercial appraisers and this guy named Wilson had made up an appraisal

00:27:53.920 --> 00:28:00.640
on my property in 1997 and came up with a value of 270 thousand dollars and i had offered this

00:28:00.640 --> 00:28:02.240
property to cody

00:28:02.240 --> 00:28:02.320
for

00:28:02.320 --> 00:28:02.880
um

00:28:02.880 --> 00:28:03.120
250.

00:28:03.120 --> 00:28:05.800
I says, Cody, I'll walk away from my business.

00:28:06.459 --> 00:28:08.760
Get everything out of here. You buy this place.

00:28:09.360 --> 00:28:12.340
And for $250,000, which was less than the appraisal,

00:28:12.459 --> 00:28:14.500
and you're happy, I'm happy.

00:28:14.659 --> 00:28:17.239
Cody never would. I gave him a copy of the appraisal.

00:28:17.479 --> 00:28:19.479
Never would come back to me with a counteroffer.

00:28:21.340 --> 00:28:24.939
So I just kept on about my business.

00:28:24.939 --> 00:28:31.399
And in 98, this Docheff guy, he comes onto the property just south of me

00:28:31.400 --> 00:28:33.200
and puts up this big circus tent.

00:28:33.860 --> 00:28:42.080
And he starts breaking concrete down to build these sewer septic tanks

00:28:42.080 --> 00:28:47.360
and manholes, you know, rings and different things that he's making.

00:28:50.000 --> 00:28:53.900
And of course, I don't remember.

00:28:54.740 --> 00:28:57.480
He was driving right across my property because he had an easement,

00:28:57.720 --> 00:28:59.820
which was fine at the time.

00:28:59.920 --> 00:29:01.380
You know, I didn't think it was going to get into.

00:29:01.400 --> 00:29:02.520
It wouldn't be any big problem.

00:29:03.400 --> 00:29:07.140
But, you know, he still hadn't made an offer on my property.

